[5] Cholera - The Gambia (Western Division)
Date: Mon, 19 Sep 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Daily Observer [edited]
<http://www.observer.gm/enews/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1918&Itemid=33>

Abdoulie Camara, a senior official at the Disease Surveillance Unit at the
department of state for Health, has warned the Gambian populace to give
extra attention to their personal hygiene to avoid getting [cholera infection].
5 patients have so far been admitted at the RVTH (Royal Victoria Teaching
Hospital) on suspicion of contracting cholera, shortly after 1 death was
reported on Mon, 19 Sep 2005, in Brikama.
Reacting to the news, Mr Camara said: "People should take an extra look at
their personal hygiene, feedings and water, and scale down their attendance
at ceremonies. They should also wash their bodies thoroughly to avoid
contraction. The entirety of West Africa is affected. And people should
avoid travelling to areas where the disease is prevalent. Many deaths have
occurred," he warned.
Mr Camara confirmed that the suspected cases and death were caused by
cholera which was contained a few months ago. He said the investigations of
the 5 suspected cases revealed that they contracted the disease while
washing the body of a person who died of cholera. He said the 5 patients
have been admitted at an isolated ward at the RVTH. "No one is allowed
access to them."
2 samples have been sent to the RVTH lab for testing. "They are being
attended by doctors and nurses at the hospital, and they are responding to
treatment,"he added.
******
[6] Cholera - Niger (Southwest)
Date: Mon, 19 Sep 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: TodayOnline.com [edited]
<http://www.todayonline.com/articles/73124.asp>

A cholera epidemic has killed 46 people in southwestern Niger since Jul
2005, according to figures quoted by state radio. The announcement followed
a visit by health minister Ari Ibrahim to the Tahoua region, where 383
cases of the highly infectious disease were recorded, the report said. The
death toll is more than twice previous figures from a national health data
agency stating that 22 people had died out of 251 reported cholera cases in
3 southwestern health districts.
Without giving a breakdown of district figures, the radio report said the
health minister's tour was to bolster efforts to contain the outbreak.
"Most of the patients have been treated and have returned home," it added.
******
[7] Cholera - Senegal (Dakar)
Date: Mon, 19 Sep 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Integrated Regional Information Networks (IRIN) [edited]
<http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/RWB.NSF/db900SID/KHII-6GE5P6?OpenDocument>

Senegal's months-long cholera epidemic has flared up once again following
severe flooding this month in the suburbs of the capital Dakar, according
to statistics from the Health Ministry on Mon, 19 Sep 2005.
The West African nation has registered a total 23 325 cases of cholera and
321 deaths in the last 9 months, the ministry said, but the number of cases
increased steeply this month, with 1031 cases from 5-11 Sep and 1110 from
12-18 Sep 2005. There were 25 deaths the 1st week of September and 21 the
next from the waterborne disease, which can kill within a day by inducing
severe vomiting and diarrhea.
"The floods have triggered an explosion in the number of cases," said Papa
Salif Sow, who heads the infectious diseases ward at Dakar's Fann hospital.
From an average 5 cases a day through Jun, Jul and Aug 2005, "since the
floods we've been seeing 45 cases of cholera per day," he told IRIN.
The Senegalese capital has been devastated by the heaviest rains seen in 2
decades, with 5600 people displaced by floods and thousands still living
with water around their ankles several weeks after the storms.
The disaster has centered on Dakar's impoverished outer suburbs, where a
lack of street drains and sewage, coupled with a breakdown in refuse
collection due to the floods, has spawned disease.
The outbreak of cholera late in 2004 in the once tidy city unnerved the
cash-strapped health authorities, who had been last faced by an epidemic in
1996.
******
[8] Cholera - Senegal (Dakar)
Date: Fri 16, Sep 2005
From: Thomas Roesel <roesel@erols.com>
Source: fr.AllAfrica.com and Wal Fadjri (Dakar) [trans. by submitter; edited]
<http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/printable/200509160435.html>

The "unwashed hands" disease continues to ravage the country. The Dakar
region, with its flooding, is uppermost among those affected areas, with 54
per cent of the cases and 60 per cent of the deaths in the country. This
increase in cholera cases was the reason for holding an interministerial
counsel on this disease at the office of the prime minister.
The interministerial counsel, dedicated to cholera and held yesterday, 15
Sep 2005, at the prime minister's office, discussed at length the urgent
measures to take in view of the recurrence of the epidemic. The "unwashed
hands" disease encompassed more area in the flooded zones as well as in
Dakar, which makes up most of these areas. With a national average of 146
cases per day during the week of 5- 11 Sep 2005, the Dakar region reported
54 per cent of the cases in the country and 60 per cent of the deaths
during that same period.
"The stagnation of rainwater, associated with poor living conditions, along
with the insufficiency of water decontamination and production facilities,
the people's attitude toward risks in hygiene matters, and the
proliferation of disease vectors, exposes the population, particularly
those in flooded areas, to a major epidemic, particularly in this context
of this permissiveness," stated the health minister in his communication to
the interministerial counsel. Before the assessment at the time of the 1st
week after the flooding (22-28 Aug 2005), there was a tendency towards an
increase, compared to the national average of 87 cases per day, as well as
more the 1 death per day on average. The second week after the flooding (29
Aug-4 Sep 2005, the trend continued with an average of 101 cases per day,
and more than the average of 1 cholera related death per day. Dakar, at
this time, becomes the region most affected with 46 per cent of the cases
in the country and 70 per cent of deaths."
This information received by the Health and Preventive Medicine minister
reveals that the flood-affected Dakar region leads, followed by Thies, with
31 per cent of the cases in the country and an average of 1 death per day.
According to the Ministry of Health and Preventive Medicine, the cholera
cases were more severe in those flooded zones, with all Dakar regions
affected, notably those of Mbao, Pikine, [and] Gudiawaye, which is the most
severely hit.
The latest epidemiological report included 174 new cholera cases and 4
deaths. The greatest increase concerns the Dakar region, with 113 new cases
and 2 deaths reported by the health authorities, who also describe 27 new
cases and 1 death in Thies. The other regions affected are Diourbel with 15
new cases and 1 death, Fatick (10 cases), Saint-Louis (5 cases), Kaolack (3
cases) and Louga (2 cases), according to the same source.
--
Thomas Roesel, MD, PhD
<roesel@erols.com>
