[9] Cholera - Guinea-Bissau
Date: Wed, 21 Sep 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: IRIN News [edited]
<http://www.irinnews.org/report.asp?ReportID=49178&SelectRegion=West_Africa&SelectCountry=GUINEA-BISSAU>

A cholera epidemic in Guinea-Bissau is showing no sign of fading, with all
regions of the impoverished country now affected and more than 4 000 new
cases of the disease reported so far in Sep 2005, officials said.
In a bulletin issued late Tue, 20 Sep 2005, the health ministry said 15 573
cases of cholera had now been recorded, up from 11 192 at the beginning of
the Sep 2005. Some 270 people have died since the epidemic first struck the
former Portuguese colony in mid-Jun 2005.
"The problem in Guinea-Bissau is that it's an epidemic that is moving out
from the towns and spreading to rural areas," said Claire-Lise Chaignat,
the leading cholera expert at the WHO. And heavy rains, which are not due
to subside until Oct 2005, make reaching those areas tricky.
"Getting people, sanitation and medicines out into rural areas is
difficult, because rains make the roads impassable and so the cholera can
continue attacking people," Michel Balima, the UN resident co-ordinator in
Guinea-Bissau, told IRIN.
When the outbreak started 3 months ago, more than 9 out of 10 cases were to
be found around the capital, Bissau -- a city of 300 000 built on low-lying
land on the banks of a muddy river estuary -- and the nearby coastal region
of Biombo to the west. Now these urban areas account for around 7 out of 10
cases, Chaignat said.
******
[10] Cholera - Guinea-Bissau
Date: Sat, 17 Sep 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: News24.com [edited]
<http://www.news24.com/News24/Africa/News/0,,2-11-1447_1772280,00.html>

At least 4400 more people were diagnosed with cholera in just 2 weeks in
the West African state of Guinea Bissau, and 35 of them have died, the
health ministry said.
"The situation is way beyond the means we have to combat it," chief medical
officer Tome Vaz said as the new figures were released on Fri, 16 Sep 2005.
The ministry said that 4400 new cases had been reported between 1 and 15
Sep 2005, and 35 people had died in the same period. The figures took the
total since the outbreak began in Jun 2005 to 264 dead and 14 660 cases.
According to a report published by non-governmental organizations at the
start of the month, Guinea Bissau is the country most affected by cholera
in the West African region.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[With an estimated population of about 1.4 million, about 1 per cent of the
population has been infected with cholera since Jun 2005.
